{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17519728","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17519728"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:15:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:15:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13071"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13071","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13071"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.28,0.15,0.06,0.49,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5508"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48810"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5508","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5508"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13071"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33780"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"111"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13181"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14668"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48810","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/48810"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 81-year-old woman presents with a six hour history of generalised and progressive  abdominal pain. The pain is constant in nature and she has never had these symptoms before. Her medical history includes hypertension, for which she takes perindopril.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination she looks unwell, with a blood pressure of 108/ 72 mmHg, pulse 100/min and temperature 37.0C. There is generalised abdominal tenderness. A CT scan is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Diverticulitis","Leaking abdominal aortic aneurysm","Acute pancreatitis","Small bowel ischaemia","Appendicitis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe scan shows dilated loops of small bowel with concentric thickening of the bowel wall.\u00a0 There is extensive stranding (inflammation) in the surrounding mesentery.\u00a0 There is also some intramural gas. This fits best with the diagnosis of \u003Cstrong\u003Esmall bowel ischaemia\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAcute pancreatitis could have a similar clinical picture, but the pain and abdominal tenderness is usually focussed on the upper abdomen.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe symptoms and signs associated with diverticulitis tender to be based in the left iliac fossa, which is not the case here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAppendicitis must always be considered in any patient who presents with acute abdominal pain. However the generalised features of symptoms and signs would be more suggestive of another cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA leaking abdominal aortic aneurysm is an important condition to consider in the older, hypertensive patient presenting with acute abdominal pain, but given the CT findings in this case, this diagnosis can be excluded.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The presence of intramural gas combined with the clinical picture suggests an ischaemic process"],"references":["Tilsed JVT, Casamassima A, Kurihara H, et al. ESTES guidelines: acute mesenteric ischaemia. Eur J Trauma Emerg Surg 2016; 42:253\u2013270"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33780"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13071"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20187"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","